layers.nm: A private company’s shares are not traded on an exchange, and ownership cannot be bought or sold.  They are also not required to share any of their financial information, making them more difficult to value than their public counterparts.  Since private companies do not have investors to satisfy, they are allowed more freedom in  their decision making.

s.t: A private company’s shares are not tradedon an exchange, and ownership cannot bebought or sold.They are also not required to share any of theirfinancial information, making them moredifficult to value than their public counterparts.Since private companies do not have investorsto satisfy, they are allowed more freedom in their decision making.

layers.nm: A public company has stocks that are freely bought and sold on an exchange.  They are required to disclose their financial information to the public, enabling anyone to read and analyze their operations.  In exchange for the funding public companies receive from investors, they must try to please their shareholders when making decisions.
